		<label>Borchardt C93</label>
		<description>Caliber: 7.65x25mm Borchardt. 8-round detachable mag. Semi-Automatic.
		
The Borchardt C93 is a semi-automatic handgun designed by Hugo Borchardt in the early 1890s, using a unique toggle-lock design. About 3,000 Borchardt pistols were produced, making it the first successful semi-auto pistol ever put in production - however, it had no significant non-commercial sales, and any military use of the C93 was limited to experiments or by officers with privately procured sidearms. Nevertheless, the pistol was extremely influential on the development of future handguns; while working at Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken (DWM), Georg Luger was tasked with selling C93 pistols abroad. Receiving an extensive list of complaints, Luger was tasked to redesign the pistol, with the final design evolving into the iconic Luger pistol. Furthermore, the C93's 7.65mm cartridge was used as the basis for the 7.63x25mm cartridge developed for Mauser's C96 pistol.</description>
